      },
      "lineNbr": 779,
      "author": {
        "id": 1001993
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-03-30T06:55:15Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yes I also agree, we could handle gracefully throwing a runtime exception instead, Impact is restoration of Synced PELs wont work automatically until restart the application",
      "parentUuid": "1fcdaf54_84d24d3e",
      "revId": "8ff14b44457d8b19147e9df2832cf47375872b61",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "521fe777_22174d04",
        "filename": "log_manager.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 779,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002680
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-03-31T08:22:09Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "My initial thought was to treat this as fatal because even though the synced files will still be present on disk, without the watcher they won’t get restored into D-Bus until some later restart. My concern was the live D-Bus state, because any client watching the interface or property changes could miss those entries completely, and we do not really control for the phosphor-logging when that next successful restart will be. So I was leaning more toward fail-fast here instead of silently running. what do you think about that tradeoff?",
      "parentUuid": "9f3210ad_21f68e12",
      "revId": "8ff14b44457d8b19147e9df2832cf47375872b61",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a74cc3b6_14f886c7",
        "filename": "log_manager.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 779,
      "author": {
        "id": 1001993
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-06T04:49:08Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003ewhat do you think about that tradeoff?\n\n\nThe biggest concern here is ,systemd will attempt to restart the application, and if all retries fail, the BMC could transition to a quiesced state. That might be a relatively heavy in this scenario i feel.\n\nDo we really want to mark the BMC as quiesced due to a failure in creating the watcher? \n\n@rameshi1@in.ibm.com Could you please share your view?",
      "parentUuid": "521fe777_22174d04",
      "revId": "8ff14b44457d8b19147e9df2832cf47375872b61",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "03423b9c_0c227138",
        "filename": "log_manager.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 779,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000427
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-06T10:31:32Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The likelihood of inotify_init1 failing is low. In such a case, we can throw an exception that propagates to the main function, causing the application to crash and trigger a restart. If it fails again, the system can retry once more, after which the BMC would transition into a quiesced state.\n\nIdeally, we should not ignore this failure silently, as certain functionalities (such as sync refresh) would not occur. Since this is part of the event log setup, it is important to explicitly flag the failure.\n\nAlso, this inotify initialization should be performed only when the redundant BMC feature is enabled.",
      "parentUuid": "a74cc3b6_14f886c7",
      "revId": "8ff14b44457d8b19147e9df2832cf47375872b61",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": false,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "5f429864_08bdf864",
        "filename": "log_manager.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 779,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002680
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-08T08:50:19Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yes, I would treat it as a fatal failure.\n\nIt is expected to be a very rare case, and in that worst-case scenario it should also generate a dump to help with debugging.",
      "parentUuid": "03423b9c_0c227138",
      "revId": "8ff14b44457d8b19147e9df2832cf47375872b61",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
